1.Bodhidharma was a semi-legendary Buddhist monk who lived during the 5th or 6th century.
2.He is traditionally credited as the transmitter of Buddhism to China, and regarded as its first Chinese patriarch.
3.According to Chinese legend, he also began the physical training of the monks of Shaolin Monastery that led to the
4.creation of Shaolin kungfu. He is known as Dámó in China and as Daruma in Japan. His name means "dharma of awakening
5. (bodhi)" in Sanskrit.[1]
6.Little contemporary biographical information on Bodhidharma is extant, and subsequent accounts became layered with
7.legend and unreliable details.[2][note 1]
8.According to the principal Chinese sources, Bodhidharma came from the Western Regions,[5][6] which refers to Central
9.Asia but may also include the Indian subcontinent, and is described as either a "Persian Central Asian"[5] or
10.a "South Indian [...] the third son of a great Indian king."[6][note 2] Throughout Buddhist art,
11.Bodhidharma is depicted as an ill-tempered, profusely-bearded, wide-eyed non-Chinese person. He is referred as "The Blue-Eyed Barbarian" (Chinese: 碧眼胡; pinyin: Bìyǎnhú) in Chan texts.[11]
12.Aside from the Chinese accounts, several popular traditions also exist regarding Bodhidharma's origins.[note 4]
13.The accounts also differ on the date of his arrival, with one early account claiming that he arrived during the Liu Song dynasty (420–479) and later accounts dating his arrival to the Liang dynasty (502–557). Bodhidharma was primarily active in the territory of the Northern Wei (386–534). Modern scholarship dates him to about the early 5th century.[16]